[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":863},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F02\u002F20\u002Fjavascript-core-50-wrapper-objects-prototype\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F02\u002F20\u002Fjavascript-core-50-wrapper-objects-prototype\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F02\u002F20\u002Fjavascript-core-50-wrapper-objects-prototype\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F02\u002F20\u002Fjavascript-core-50-wrapper-objects-prototype\u002F":838,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F02\u002F20\u002Fjavascript-core-50-wrapper-objects-prototype\u002F":847},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20210220\u002F2098058170\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":821,"date":822,"description":823,"extension":824,"lang":825,"meta":826,"navigation":279,"path":827,"readingMinutes":828,"seo":829,"standalone":830,"stem":831,"tags":832,"tldr":835,"updated":822,"url":836,"__hash__":837},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-50-wrapper-objects-prototype.md","JavaScript Core (50) - Inheritance & the Prototype Chain: Primitive Wrapper Objects and Their Link to Prototypes","1001021554",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":816},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,77,84,119,122,164,170,218,224,231,246,252,356,359,436,442,449,624,633,795,799,812],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Next up we'll look at the relationship between primitive values and their wrapper objects. If you can get these two straight in your head, you'll actually run into a lot fewer bugs.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"primitive-wrapper-objects-and-their-link-to-prototypes","Primitive Wrapper Objects and Their Link to Prototypes",[17,25,26],{},"Let's start with plain primitive values. When you declare one, it usually looks like this:",[28,29,34],"pre",{"className":30,"code":31,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var myName = 'ray';\nconsole.log(myName); \u002F\u002F ray\n","js","",[35,36,37,60],"code",{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,39,42,46,50,53,57],"span",{"class":40,"line":41},"line",1,[38,43,45],{"class":44},"sWyjQ","var",[38,47,49],{"class":48},"sMAXC"," myName ",[38,51,52],{"class":44},"=",[38,54,56],{"class":55},"sTRMh"," 'ray'",[38,58,59],{"class":48},";\n",[38,61,63,66,70,73],{"class":40,"line":62},2,[38,64,65],{"class":48},"console.",[38,67,69],{"class":68},"sj_SG","log",[38,71,72],{"class":48},"(myName); ",[38,74,76],{"class":75},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F ray\n",[17,78,79,80,83],{},"In the browser console this shows up as plain black text (too lazy to screenshot it). Now say we want to turn that value into all uppercase. We can use a method from the ",[35,81,82],{},"String"," wrapper object to do it:",[28,85,87],{"className":30,"code":86,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var myName = 'ray';\nconsole.log(myName.toUpperCase()); \u002F\u002F RAY\n",[35,88,89,101],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,90,91,93,95,97,99],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,92,45],{"class":44},[38,94,49],{"class":48},[38,96,52],{"class":44},[38,98,56],{"class":55},[38,100,59],{"class":48},[38,102,103,105,107,110,113,116],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,104,65],{"class":48},[38,106,69],{"class":68},[38,108,109],{"class":48},"(myName.",[38,111,112],{"class":68},"toUpperCase",[38,114,115],{"class":48},"()); ",[38,117,118],{"class":75},"\u002F\u002F RAY\n",[17,120,121],{},"Besides the usual way of declaring a value, there's another way — the one I've kept hammering on about: \"a variable declared with a wrapper object is a different type, and it behaves differently.\" So this is just a demo. Please don't actually declare things like this in real code.",[28,123,125],{"className":30,"code":124,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var myName = new String('ray');\nconsole.log(myName.toUpperCase()); \u002F\u002F RAY\n",[35,126,127,150],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,128,129,131,133,135,138,141,144,147],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,130,45],{"class":44},[38,132,49],{"class":48},[38,134,52],{"class":44},[38,136,137],{"class":44}," new",[38,139,140],{"class":68}," String",[38,142,143],{"class":48},"(",[38,145,146],{"class":55},"'ray'",[38,148,149],{"class":48},");\n",[38,151,152,154,156,158,160,162],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,153,65],{"class":48},[38,155,69],{"class":68},[38,157,109],{"class":48},[38,159,112],{"class":68},[38,161,115],{"class":48},[38,163,118],{"class":75},[17,165,166,167,169],{},"As you can see, the result is the same, even though this way of declaring gives you an object instead of a ",[35,168,82],{}," primitive:",[28,171,173],{"className":30,"code":172,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var myName = new String('ray');\nconsole.log(myName.toUpperCase()); \u002F\u002F RAY\ntypeof(myName); \u002F\u002F object\n",[35,174,175,193,207],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,176,177,179,181,183,185,187,189,191],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,178,45],{"class":44},[38,180,49],{"class":48},[38,182,52],{"class":44},[38,184,137],{"class":44},[38,186,140],{"class":68},[38,188,143],{"class":48},[38,190,146],{"class":55},[38,192,149],{"class":48},[38,194,195,197,199,201,203,205],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,196,65],{"class":48},[38,198,69],{"class":68},[38,200,109],{"class":48},[38,202,112],{"class":68},[38,204,115],{"class":48},[38,206,118],{"class":75},[38,208,210,213,215],{"class":40,"line":209},3,[38,211,212],{"class":44},"typeof",[38,214,72],{"class":48},[38,216,217],{"class":75},"\u002F\u002F object\n",[17,219,220,221,223],{},"But going through this route lets us see all the methods the wrapper object has available — including the ",[35,222,112],{}," method we just used:",[17,225,226],{},[227,228],"img",{"alt":229,"src":230},"All methods available on the String wrapper object shown via proto","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202021-02-20%2023.21.38.png",[17,232,233,234,237,238,241,242,245],{},"On top of that, ",[35,235,236],{},"String()"," itself is a function — it's just used as a constructor with ",[35,239,240],{},"new"," — so it has its own ",[35,243,244],{},"prototype"," too.",[17,247,248,249,251],{},"And if you want to add your own method to ",[35,250,82],{}," via the prototype, that's no problem at all. Same idea as in the course example:",[28,253,255],{"className":30,"code":254,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var myName = new String('ray');\n\nString.prototype.lastText = function () {\n  return this[this.length - 1];\n}\nconsole.log(myName.lastText()); \u002F\u002F y\n",[35,256,257,275,281,305,334,340],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,258,259,261,263,265,267,269,271,273],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,260,45],{"class":44},[38,262,49],{"class":48},[38,264,52],{"class":44},[38,266,137],{"class":44},[38,268,140],{"class":68},[38,270,143],{"class":48},[38,272,146],{"class":55},[38,274,149],{"class":48},[38,276,277],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,278,280],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":279},true,"\n",[38,282,283,286,289,291,293,296,299,302],{"class":40,"line":209},[38,284,82],{"class":285},"sCcAr",[38,287,288],{"class":48},".",[38,290,244],{"class":285},[38,292,288],{"class":48},[38,294,295],{"class":68},"lastText",[38,297,298],{"class":44}," =",[38,300,301],{"class":44}," function",[38,303,304],{"class":48}," () {\n",[38,306,308,311,314,317,320,322,325,328,331],{"class":40,"line":307},4,[38,309,310],{"class":44},"  return",[38,312,313],{"class":285}," this",[38,315,316],{"class":48},"[",[38,318,319],{"class":285},"this",[38,321,288],{"class":48},[38,323,324],{"class":285},"length",[38,326,327],{"class":44}," -",[38,329,330],{"class":285}," 1",[38,332,333],{"class":48},"];\n",[38,335,337],{"class":40,"line":336},5,[38,338,339],{"class":48},"}\n",[38,341,343,345,347,349,351,353],{"class":40,"line":342},6,[38,344,65],{"class":48},[38,346,69],{"class":68},[38,348,109],{"class":48},[38,350,295],{"class":68},[38,352,115],{"class":48},[38,354,355],{"class":75},"\u002F\u002F y\n",[17,357,358],{},"With this approach we can modify the prototype methods of any wrapper object — and it works even when you're using a plain primitive:",[28,360,362],{"className":30,"code":361,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var myName = 'ray';\n\nString.prototype.lastText = function () {\n  return this[this.length - 1];\n}\nconsole.log(myName.lastText()); \u002F\u002F y\n",[35,363,364,376,380,398,418,422],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,365,366,368,370,372,374],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,367,45],{"class":44},[38,369,49],{"class":48},[38,371,52],{"class":44},[38,373,56],{"class":55},[38,375,59],{"class":48},[38,377,378],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,379,280],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":279},[38,381,382,384,386,388,390,392,394,396],{"class":40,"line":209},[38,383,82],{"class":285},[38,385,288],{"class":48},[38,387,244],{"class":285},[38,389,288],{"class":48},[38,391,295],{"class":68},[38,393,298],{"class":44},[38,395,301],{"class":44},[38,397,304],{"class":48},[38,399,400,402,404,406,408,410,412,414,416],{"class":40,"line":307},[38,401,310],{"class":44},[38,403,313],{"class":285},[38,405,316],{"class":48},[38,407,319],{"class":285},[38,409,288],{"class":48},[38,411,324],{"class":285},[38,413,327],{"class":44},[38,415,330],{"class":285},[38,417,333],{"class":48},[38,419,420],{"class":40,"line":336},[38,421,339],{"class":48},[38,423,424,426,428,430,432,434],{"class":40,"line":342},[38,425,65],{"class":48},[38,427,69],{"class":68},[38,429,109],{"class":48},[38,431,295],{"class":68},[38,433,115],{"class":48},[38,435,355],{"class":75},[17,437,438,439,441],{},"Every primitive has its own wrapper object — strings, numbers, you name it. And because the prototype is shared, once we modify ",[35,440,82],{},"'s prototype, we can use that method straight away. That's the whole idea behind the prototype.",[17,443,444,445,448],{},"Of course JavaScript has plenty of other constructors too, including the ",[35,446,447],{},"new Date()"," we reach for all the time. When you work with dates, you usually have to reassemble the pieces yourself. But if you put the prototype concept to good use, you can write something like this:",[28,450,452],{"className":30,"code":451,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"var date = new Date();\nDate.prototype.getFillDate = function () {\n  var dd = String(this.getDate());\n  var mm = String(this.getMonth() + 1);\n  var yyyy = String(this.getFullYear());\n\n  return yyyy + '\u002F' + mm + '\u002F' + dd;\n}\n\nconsole.log(date.getFillDate()); \u002F\u002F 2021\u002F2\u002F20\n",[35,453,454,471,491,515,545,567,571,597,602,607],{"__ignoreMap":33},[38,455,456,458,461,463,465,468],{"class":40,"line":41},[38,457,45],{"class":44},[38,459,460],{"class":48}," date ",[38,462,52],{"class":44},[38,464,137],{"class":44},[38,466,467],{"class":68}," Date",[38,469,470],{"class":48},"();\n",[38,472,473,476,478,480,482,485,487,489],{"class":40,"line":62},[38,474,475],{"class":285},"Date",[38,477,288],{"class":48},[38,479,244],{"class":285},[38,481,288],{"class":48},[38,483,484],{"class":68},"getFillDate",[38,486,298],{"class":44},[38,488,301],{"class":44},[38,490,304],{"class":48},[38,492,493,496,499,501,503,505,507,509,512],{"class":40,"line":209},[38,494,495],{"class":44},"  var",[38,497,498],{"class":48}," dd ",[38,500,52],{"class":44},[38,502,140],{"class":68},[38,504,143],{"class":48},[38,506,319],{"class":285},[38,508,288],{"class":48},[38,510,511],{"class":68},"getDate",[38,513,514],{"class":48},"());\n",[38,516,517,519,522,524,526,528,530,532,535,538,541,543],{"class":40,"line":307},[38,518,495],{"class":44},[38,520,521],{"class":48}," mm ",[38,523,52],{"class":44},[38,525,140],{"class":68},[38,527,143],{"class":48},[38,529,319],{"class":285},[38,531,288],{"class":48},[38,533,534],{"class":68},"getMonth",[38,536,537],{"class":48},"() ",[38,539,540],{"class":44},"+",[38,542,330],{"class":285},[38,544,149],{"class":48},[38,546,547,549,552,554,556,558,560,562,565],{"class":40,"line":336},[38,548,495],{"class":44},[38,550,551],{"class":48}," yyyy ",[38,553,52],{"class":44},[38,555,140],{"class":68},[38,557,143],{"class":48},[38,559,319],{"class":285},[38,561,288],{"class":48},[38,563,564],{"class":68},"getFullYear",[38,566,514],{"class":48},[38,568,569],{"class":40,"line":342},[38,570,280],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":279},[38,572,574,576,578,580,583,586,588,590,592,594],{"class":40,"line":573},7,[38,575,310],{"class":44},[38,577,551],{"class":48},[38,579,540],{"class":44},[38,581,582],{"class":55}," '\u002F'",[38,584,585],{"class":44}," +",[38,587,521],{"class":48},[38,589,540],{"class":44},[38,591,582],{"class":55},[38,593,585],{"class":44},[38,595,596],{"class":48}," dd;\n",[38,598,600],{"class":40,"line":599},8,[38,601,339],{"class":48},[38,603,605],{"class":40,"line":604},9,[38,606,280],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":279},[38,608,610,612,614,617,619,621],{"class":40,"line":609},10,[38,611,65],{"class":48},[38,613,69],{"class":68},[38,615,616],{"class":48},"(date.",[38,618,484],{"class":68},[38,620,115],{"class":48},[38,622,623],{"class":75},"\u002F\u002F 2021\u002F2\u002F20\n",[17,625,626,627,629,630,632],{},"One thing to watch out for here: we're adding ",[35,628,484],{}," onto ",[35,631,244],{},", so you have to go through the constructor. Otherwise, if you just run the code below, you'll get an error:",[28,634,636],{"className":30,"code":635,"language":32,"meta":33,"style":33},"Date.prototype.getFillDate = function () {\n  \u002F\u002F We use String for the type conversion here mainly to avoid a subtle bug:\n  \u002F\u002F if the extracted date parts come out as numbers, the + operator would add\n  \u002F\u002F them together instead of concatenating them.\n  \u002F\u002F ex: return yyyy + mm + + dd;\n  var dd = String(this.getDate());\n  var mm = String(this.getMonth() + 1);\n  var yyyy = String(this.getFullYear());\n\n  return yyyy + '\u002F' + mm + '\u002F' + dd;\n}\n\nconsole.log(Date.getFillDate()); \u002F\u002F TypeError: Date.getFillDate is not a function\n",[35,637,638,656,661,666,671,676,696,722,742,746,768,773,778],{"__ignor